   current study investigated whether and how empathic neural responses to
   pain were modulated by the perceived reputation of others. Action
   histories reflecting individuals' past cooperation or betrayal actions
   in the repeated prisoner's dilemma game were introduced as an index of
   reputation. We assessed brain activity with functional magnetic
   resonance imaging while the participants observed individuals with a
   good or bad reputation receiving or not receiving pain. The results
   indicated that the participants exhibited reduced empathic responses in
   AI and dACC to the individual who had a bad reputation relative to the
   one who had a good reputation, suggesting that their empathy for pain
