Abstract = {{Connectivity in the brain is the most promising approach to explain
   human behavior. Here we develop a focused information criterion for
   graphical models to determine brain connectivity tailored to specific
   research questions. All efforts are concentrated on high-dimensional
   settings where the number of nodes in the graph is larger than the
   number of samples. The graphical models may include autoregressive times
   series components, they can relate graphs from different subjects or
   pool data via random effects. The proposed method selects a graph with a
   small estimated mean squared error for a user-specified focus. The
   performance of the proposed method is assessed on simulated data sets
   and on a resting state functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) data
   set where often the number of nodes in the estimated graph is equal to
