Pages = {{4596-4609}},
Month = {{NOV}},
Abstract = {{The superior temporal sulcus (STS) is considered a hub for social
   perception and cognition, including the perception of faces and human
   motion, as well as understanding others' actions, mental states, and
   language. However, the functional organization of the STS remains
   debated: Is this broad region composed of multiple functionally distinct
   modules, each specialized for a different process, or are STS subregions
   multifunctional, contributing to multiple processes? Is the STS
   spatially organized, and if so, what are the dominant features of this
   organization? We address these questions by measuring STS responses to a
   range of social and linguistic stimuli in the same set of human
   participants, using fMRI. We find a number of STS subregions that
   respond selectively to certain types of social input, organized along a
   posterior-to-anterior axis. We also identify regions of overlapping
   response to multiple contrasts, including regions responsive to both
   language and theory of mind, faces and voices, and faces and biological
   motion. Thus, the human STS contains both relatively domain-specific
   areas, and regions that respond to multiple types of social information.}},
