Title = {{Aberrant functioning of the theory-of-mind network in children and
   adolescents with autism}},
Journal = {{MOLECULAR AUTISM}},
Year = {{2015}},
Volume = {{6}},
Month = {{OCT 27}},
Abstract = {{Background: Theory-of-mind (ToM), the ability to infer people's thoughts
   and feelings, is a pivotal skill in effective social interactions.
   Individuals with autism spectrum disorders (ASD) have been found to have
   altered ToM skills, which significantly impacts the quality of their
   social interactions. Neuroimaging studies have reported altered
   activation of the ToM cortical network, especially in adults with
   autism, yet little is known about the brain responses underlying ToM in
   younger individuals with ASD. This functional magnetic resonance imaging
   (fMRI) study investigated the neural mechanisms underlying ToM in
   high-functioning children and adolescents with ASD and matched typically
   developing (TD) peers.
   Methods: fMRI data were acquired from 13 participants with ASD and 13 TD
   control participants while they watched animations involving two
   ``interacting{''} geometrical shapes.
   Results: Participants with ASD showed significantly reduced activation,
   relative to TD controls, in regions considered part of the ToM network,
   the mirror network, and the cerebellum. Functional connectivity analyses
   revealed underconnectivity between frontal and posterior regions during
   task performance in the ASD participants.
   Conclusions: Overall, the findings of this study reveal disruptions in
   the brain circuitry underlying ToM in ASD at multiple levels, including
   decreased activation and decreased functional connectivity.}},
