Month = {{SEP}},
Abstract = {{Humans display individual variability in cooperative behavior. While an
   ever-growing body of research has investigated the neural correlates of
   task-specific cooperation, the mechanisms by which
   situation-independent, stable differences in cooperation render behavior
   consistent across a wide range of situations remain elusive. Addressing
   this issue, we show that the individual tendency to behave in a
   prosocial or individualistic manner can be predicted from the functional
   resting-state connectome. More specifically, connections of the
   cinguloopercular network which supports goal-directed behavior encode
   cooperative tendency. Effects of virtual lesions to this network on the
   efficacy of information exchange throughout the brain corroborate our
   findings. These results shed light on the neural mechanisms underlying
   individualists' and prosocials' habitual social decisions by showing
   that reliance on the cinguloopercular task-control network predicts
   stable cooperative behavior. Based on this evidence, we provide a
   unifying framework for the interpretation of functional imaging and
   behavioral studies of cooperative behavior. (C) 2015 Elsevier Inc. All
